{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170975/1938010601/0007.xml":{"full_text":"NATIONAL NEWS\nTHE UNEMPLOYMENT\nCANVASS SUGGESTS\nA 10,870,000 TOTAL\nResults of November Count\nGiven Roosevelt by John\nD. Biggers\nWashington, Jan. I\u2014(AP) \u2014The\nnational unemployment census in\nformed President Roosevelt today\nthat the total of the nation\u2019s unem\nployed lay between 7,822,912 and a\npossible maximum of 10,870,000.\nIts findings were based upon the\nfact that a voluntary registration of\nthe unemployed conducted between\nNovember 16 and November 20,\n1937, showed 7,822,912 to be, by\ntheir own testimony, out of work\nand wanting work, while a simul\ntaneous house-to-house canvass in\nselected areas indicated that this\ntotal was but 72 per cent complete.\nWhen Breadwinner Is Idle\nIn making this report to the chief\nexecutive. John D. Biggers, adminis\ntrator of the census, said. \u201cIt is\nnot to be assumed that because a\ncertain number of people are job\nless, the same number of joos must\nbe created to bring a return to nor\nmal conditions.\" He added:\n\"When the usual family beradwin\nner is idle, two or perhaps more mem\nbers of the family may enter the la\nbor market. Conversely, when the\nbreadwinner is satisfactorily reem\nployed other members of the family\nmay withdraw from the labor market.\n\"Then, too, you recognize, but it\nshould perhaps be emphasized, that\nthe number of people who reported\nthemselves as unemployed should not\nhe confused with the number of peo\nple who need financial assistance or\nrelief. Many people consider them\nselves unemployed who are financially\nnot compelled to work.\n\u201cWorkers by Hslilt''\n\"Irrespective of their need, when\nthey seek employment, they enter the\nlabor market and compete with others\nwho have jobs or vitally need jobs.\nThey are therefore, a factor in the un\nemployment problem though they\nmay never seek relief.\u201d\nOf the 7.822,812 who reported them\nselves unemployed, a total of 2,001,877\nwere emergency relief workers. Wom\nen who voluntarily registered as out\nof work comprised 1,996,699, including\nthose doing emergency relief work.\n\"The unemployed,\u201d Biggers\u2019 lette\"\nto the President said, \u201cmay be divided\ninto two classes. One class represents\nthose regular workers for wages who\nalways work, when work is available,\nregardless of their immediate economic\nstatus. Work to them is not only a\nmeans of livelihood but a habit of life.\nThese unemployed are clearly a part\nof the regular labor market.\n\u201cWorkers by Choice\u201d\n\"There is also a second group con\nsisting of those who are not regular\nworkers for wages such as house\nwives who seek wage jobs only when\nthe family breadwinner is idle;\ndaughters or sons who take jobs\nthrough choice rather than neces\nsity; unpaid family workers on farms\nand in family stores, who seek wage\njobs only when family income needs\naugmenting; retired people who, be\ncause savings have been depleted, de\ncide to enter the labor market, again.\nTo this class unemployment is a\nstatus depending on their current in\nclinations and temporary economic\nconditions.\n\u2018This second group made up of the\noccasional workers for wages might\nnot take the trouble to respond to a\nvoluntary registration but might\nreadily be reminded to relate to a\ncensus enumerator their current in\nclination to work. For example, the\nproportion of women who reported\nthemselves as unemployed was greater\nin the enumerative census than in the\nregistration, though both exceed the\npercentage of women reporting as\nunemployed in the 1930 census. It is\nexpected that our detailed analysis\n\u2022will throw further light on this and\nsimilar questions.\n72 Per Cent Reported\n\"Considering all these factors, we\ndo not claim provable accuracy for\nany one figure. The true number of\nthose who considered themselves to\ntally unemployed, able to work and\nwanting work, in our opinion lies be\ntween 7,822,912, the number who re\nsponded to the registration and 10,-\n*70,000, the number indicated by the\nenumerative census.\"\nThe voluntary registration was con\nducted through questionnaires left at\nevery house by the mailman. The re\ncipients could fill them out and re\nturn them to the unemployment cen\nsus as they chose. The house to house\ncanvass, conducted for the purpose\nof checking the comparative com\npleteness of the voluntary registra\ntion, reached 1,950,000 persons, and\nindicated that, according to the report,\nonly some 72 per cent of the unem\nployed voluntarily reported them\nselves as occupying that status.\nResponse Considered High\nA statement, issued by the census,\nsimultaneously with Blggers's report\nto the President expressed the follow,\ning conclusions:\n\"That the care with which the un\nemployment report cards were filled\nout surpassed all expectations.\n\"That the most careful check in\nthe field and in tabulating resulted In\nrejection of less than 6 per cent of all\nthe cards sent In, as compared with\nan anticipated 10 to 20 per cent.\n\"Thae experts regard the ratio of\nreturn from the voluntary registra\ntion as exceptionally high for any\ntype of voluntary registration.\n\"That the number of people who\nreported themselves as unemployed\nshould not be confused with the num\nber of people who nee3 financial as\nsistance or relief.\n\u201cThat the present report reflects\nthe decline in employment, during the\nearlier stages of the current business\nrecession, but not the subsequent\ntrend.\nCross-Section Available Any Time\n\"That if additional information is\ndesired by the President, beyond that\ncurrently obtainable from usual sta\ntistical sources, it would be possible,\nwith cooperation of the postofflee de\npartment, to make at any given fu\nture date a cross-sectional enumera\ntion which should he of value to the\nPresident and Congress,\n\"That this cross-check, In addition\nto all other work scheduled for (he\nunemployment censii\u00df organization,\ncould be carried through for substan\ntially less than the $6,000,000 budgeted\nfor the purpose of this census.\"\nSummarizing the method by which\nthe voluntary cenaus was conducted,\nthe statement said some 86,000,000\nquestionnaire cards were printed,\nwith at least one card delivered to\neach of 32,000,000 homes, one placed\nin every postofflee box nnd one\ngiven to every person who called at.\nthe postofflee- for general delivery\nmail.\nBiggers's letter promised for to\nmorrow a breakdown of the figures\nby states and iater figures for coun\nties and cities of more lhan 10,000\ninhabitants.\nSOCIAL SECURITY AIDS\n2,100,000 A MONTH\nWashington, Jan. 2 (AP) \u2014The\nsocial security board reported today\nthat over 2.100,000 needy persons\nthe aged, the blind and dependent\nchildren\u2014were receiving monthly aid\nunder the social security program.\nChairman Arthur J. Altmeyer said\nthe average monthly payment for old\nage. assif> a nee and for blind was\n$25180, /nd the average payment for\ndependent children was $27 per fam\nily.\nFEDERAL TOTE\u2019\nRAPPED BY BYRD,\nURGING ECONOMY\nVirginian Adds Caustic Com\nment to Statement He'll\nSupport Cut in U. S. High\nway Funds\nWashington, Jan. I\u2014(AP1 \u2014(AP) \u2014Senator\nHarry F. Byrd (D\u201e Va.) coupled a\nstatement today that he would sup\nport President Roosevelt\u2019s proposed\nreduction in the federal appropriation\nfor roads with a demand that at the\nsame time \u201cthe extravagances and\nluxuries of government get the ax\nand by a major operation.\u201d\nSince July 1, he said, the federal\ngovernment had spent. $300,000,000\nmore than in the same period of last\nyear, exploding \"the myth of spending\nourselves into prosperity.\n\u201cWe are spending as much or more\nthan ever, and times are getting\nworse,\u201d he said. \u201cOur revenue will\nnot reach the estimates because of\nthe business recession. I predict that\nthe defiicit for the fiscal year. 1938,\nwill be more than double the estimate\nmade.\n\"The crisis is great, and drastic and\ndetermined action is necessary to\navoid a huge increase in general tax\nation, because our financial solvency\ndemands that the budget be balanced\nsoon.\u201d\nSenator Byrd said he not only would\nsupport the proposed reduction in fed\neral road funds but would support\n\"any other expenditure reduction pro\ngram he (the President) proposes.\"\n\u201cWaste and Extravagance\"\n\u201cI am confident,\" he said, 'that those\nin the Senate with whom I have been\ncooperating for four years in support\nof a balanced budget will do likewise,\nas we recognize the perilous situa\ntion that faces the country. We are\nnow in the eighth consecutive deficit\nyear.\u201d\nFirst, however, he said expenses\nshould be reduced by \u201cthe savings\nthat would come from eliminating\nthe waste and extravagance that exist\nin the overlapping and duplicated ac\ntivities in hundreds of federal bu\nreaus.\" In four years, he said, federal\nemployes in Washington had been\ndoubled, the ordinary expenses of gov\nernment, excluding emergency expen\nditures. had been increased by 100\nper cent, and 50 new agencies and\n\u201cmany more new bureaus and subdi\nvisions\" had been created.\n\"This federal jungle at Washington\noffers a vast, opportunity to save mil\nlions of dollars without impairing the\nessential functions of government,\u201d\nthe Virginian declared. \"Legislation\nis not necessary except in few in\nstances, as the savings can be made\nin the budget.\"\nSenator Byrd said he would support\nthe load fund reduction although he\nbelieved that mdliey spent on roads\nwas for one \u201cof the most useful pur\nposes.\nCONGRESS PROBERS\nTO BE ACTIVE AGAIN\nWashington. Jan. 2\u2014 (AP)\u2014 Special\ninvestigating committees are sched\nuled to look into such far-reaching\nsubjects as unemployment, civil liber\nties and railroad financing uuring the\ncongressional session beginning tomor\nrow.\nThe special unemployment and re\nlief committee hended by Senator\nByrnes (D., S. C.) intends to begin\nhearings Tuesday. Byrnes said the\ncommittee would make a broad sur\nvey of causes, effects and possible\ncures of unemployment.\nWitnesses already called include\nboth industrial and labor leaders.\nWilliam Knudsen, president of General\nMotors, has agreed to appear Thurs\nday. Among others asked to testify\nare hammot du Pont, Myron C. Taylor,\nWilliam Green and John L. Lewis.\nThe civil liberties committee, which\nSenator La Kollette (P\u201e Wis.l heads,\nhas made an intensive preliminary\nsurvey of socalled vigilante groups\nand employer associations, and is ex\npected to call officials of business or\nganizations to hearings soon.\nNumerous other investigations have\nbeen proposed.\nRevival of Court Bill Fight\nTo Disturb Congress Session\nDemocratic Foe* of Roosevelts\u2019 Plan Face Tests of\nPopularity in Coming Primaries Little Talk\nHeard of White House Retaliation\nBy KIRKK I* SIMPSON\nWashington, lan. I\u2014(AP1 \u2014(AP) \u2014Echoes\nM the old battle over the court bill,\nstrangely Infrequent in the special\nsession, seem likely to be heard again\nin the regular meeting of Congress\nbeginning next week.\nWithin little more than three\nmonths comes the first premarles of\nthe 1938 congressional contest. Illinois\nparty polls to pick senatorial and\nother candidates fall on April 12 and\non Mav 3 Indiana follows. From then\non until late September several states\nwill be bolding primaries every\nmonlh.\nEspecial Interest centers upon the\nIndiana primary. Senator Frederick\nVan Nuys, whose scat Is at stake,\nwas one of the half dozen Senate\nDemocrats who boited presidential\nleadership on the court bill. During\nthe long drawn battle it was freely\npredicted that disciplinary party ac\ntion would be taken against the\nrebels. Yet there has been no talk\nof administration reprisals since then.\nClark Will Fare Test\nIt will be August before the sec\nond active Democratic Senate foe of\nthe court bill faces a primary teat.\nSenator Bennett Champ Clark of\nMissouri goes up for reindorsement\nby Missouri Democrats August 2.\nDuring September other Democratic\ncourt bill bolters like McCarran of\nNevada, Tydlngs of Maryland, George\nof Georgia and Lonergan of Connecti\ncut will follow.\nPolitical observers attach Im\nportance to the fact that the special\nsession saw no revival of charges\nthat the administration was prepar\ning to seek the scalps of bolter* in\nthe primaries. A direct threat was\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN: SPRINGFIELD, MASS.: THURSDAY, JANUARY 6, 1938\nHARROWING TALES\nOF YACHTING TRIP\nTOLD BY SURVIVORS\nPerfunctory Prosecution, If\nAny, Planned for Two Held\nIn Murder of \u2018Half-Mad\u2019\nMorgan\nLos Angeles, Dec. 31\u2014(AP)\u2014Ex\nciting details of murder, piracy, five\ndays of terrorism and near-starvation\naboard the luxurious yacht Aafje\ncame out today for the first time In\nstories the survivors told federal\nauthorities.\nTheir stories sounded like some of\nthe stark fiction of Joseph Conrad and\nHerman Melville.\nThey told how 28-year-old Jack\nMorgan, charterer of the yacht, slew\nthe wealthy owner, Dwight L. Fauld\ning, 49, Santa Barbara hotel man,\nsoon after their cruise started.\nThey related harrowing details of\nhow Morgan, apparently half-mad, a\npistol in each side of his belt, beat\nand scolded nearly everyone else\naboard, almost caused the death of an\neight-year-old boy, and how even be\nfore the Faulding killing, he at\ntempted an amorous conquest of a\npretty, 21-year-o!d nurse, slugging\nher almost unconscious.\nYouth Kills Morgan\nThey told how Robert Horne, 27.\nrelieved the nightmarish situation on\nChristmas day by bashing Morgan\u2019s\nhead in with a marlin spike and how\nHorne and another amateur crew\nman dumped Morgan into shark\ninfested waters off the Mexican west\ncoast.\nFederal authorities Ailed murder\ncharges against Horne and his com\npanion. George Spernak. 19. but. indi\ncated the prosecution, if any, would\nbe perfunctory.\nAssuming Morgan had plunged to\nhis doom, federal agents charged\nHorne and Spernak with causing his\ndeath by drowning.\nJohn Hanson, federal\" bureau of in\nvestigation chief hpre, said the youths\ntold him Horne felled Morgan with a\nspike and they dumped him overboard\nHanson, federal bureau of investiga\ntion chief here, said the youths told\nhim Horne felled Morgan with a spike\nand they dumped him overboard about\n10 miles from shore, not knowing\nwhether he was dead.\nThe youths and other members of\nthe original cruise party of eight,\nHanson said, reported Morgan killed\nFaulding three hours after the 58-\nfoot: schooner yacht left San Pedro\non December 20th. While Faulding\nwas at the helm. Morgan suddenly\nappeared with a pistol, said \u201cget away\nfrom that wheel, I'm taking com\nmand here,\" and then shot him when\nhe tried to argue.\nHorne and Spernak, a former Gran\nville, N. Y.. football star, were ordered\nheld incommunicado pending arraign\nment. Morgan's 17-year-cld wife, the\nformer Lillian Cassanova of New Or\nleans, was held under $2500 bond as a\nmaterial witness.\nHanson said Mrs Morgan told him\nher husband \"seemed to go crazy\" as\nhe shot Faulding and then kept the\nothers tn terrified subjection. He\nforced her to stand guard with a\npistol at times when he slept, she\nsaid.\nMorgan, a house-boy who managed\nto charter the yacht for a two-day\ncruise to Santa Catalina Island,\nseverely rationed the scant supply of\nfood and water to the others, but\ntook plenty for himself, members of\nthe party told Hanson.\nThe party had been without food\nfor three days when a naval plane\nfound the yacht Wednesday, unable\nto make port and with an \u201cSOS\"\nsmeared on a sail with black oil. A\ncoast guard cutter towed the Aafje\ninto San Pedro late yesterday.\nThe others aboard were Mrs Lucille\nTurner, Faulding\u2019s fiancee, and her\neight-year-old son, Robert, and Elsie\nBerdan, a nurse Morgan had hired\nfor his wife, an expectant mother.\nA puzzle in the weird case was the\nquestion of what Morgan planned to\ndo with the yacht and the party. Al\nthough the craft had only about two\ndays food supply aboard federal men\ntheorized Morgan may have expected\nto pick up supplies along the Mexi\ncan coast.\nAIR-TANK BUST CAUSES\nABOUT $50,000 DAMAGE\nHolliston, Jan. 2\u2014(AP)\u2014An air\ncompression tank explosion today\nripped a hole through the side of\nthe Holliston Water company pump\ning station, causing damage, estimated\nby Treasurer Kenneth Young, of\n$50,000.\nEngineer R. M. McDonald said he\ndiscovered a fire near one of the\ncompression tanks soon after he\nstarted the station\u2019s Diesel engines.\nThe explosion came, he said, while\nhe was in his house nearby, tele\nphoning for fire apparatus.\nvoiced in the wake of the court fight\nby Senator Guffey of Pennsylvania,\nthen heading the Democratic sena\ntorial campaign committee. It ran\ncounter to the Insistence of other\nadministration leaders In the Senate\nthat no reprisals against the rebels\nwould be attempted. Vice-President\nGarner raised the no reprisals slo\ngan when he intervened to end the\ncontest and sink the Roosevelt court\nbill Into the dust of a committee\npigeon hole, where It still remains.\nBoth Questions Ignored\nWhen Congress quit last summer,\nstill In turmoil over the court bill\nfight and appointment of Senator\nHugo L. Black to the supreme court,\nrevival of both mattors was widely\nexpected when it reconvened. The\nadded Incentive to debate of Black's\nadmitted former membership in the\nKu Klux Klun followed. Yet both\nmatters were all but Ignored in the\nspecial session. The more urgent\nproblem of the business recession, the\nstruggle over nntilynchlng maneu\nvers, farm legislation and the House\nsplit over the wage-hour bill took\nthe congressional stage.\nWith the 1938 primary dates so\nclose at hand, both the court bill\nfight and Black's appointment might\nget an airing In the regular session\nif anticourt bill senators detect any\nsign tnat the administration Is mov\ning behind the scenes to sweep\nparty bolters Into the political dis\ncard.\nA policy of strict neutrality at the\nWhite House In the primaries is\ntraditional. It has rarely been broken\nby any President in any obvious\nfashion.\nAuto Deqths Pass 40,000\nFirst l une in U. S. History\n40,300 Dead and 1,060,000 Injured in 1937 Traffic Ac\ncidents, Count Reveals Weekend Takes 217\nLives by Violence, Including 167 On Highways\nNew York, Jan. 2 A horrible\nscreeching 1 of rubber on pavement\na rending crash screams of a\nwoman and children Then moans\nand whimpering.\nThe headline said, \u201cFive Dead in\nAuto Crash,\" echoing hundreds of\nothers like it daily throughout the\nnation.\nThe year 1937 ends and someone\nwith a grisly flair for statistics has\nadded things up. Tonight he an\nnounced:\u2014\n\u201cDeath on American highways dur\ning 1937 smashes all records. Reaches\n40,300 \u2014nearly 3000 more killed than\nthe total of American army battle\ncasualties during the World war!\u201d\nThe streets and roads of the United\nStates paved with more blood than\nthe battlefields of France, the statis\ntician says, adding:\n\u201cNot only did accident fatalities sky\nrocket over 40,000 for the first time in\nthe history of the automobile, but the\nnumber of injuries exceeded one mil\nlion.\u201d\nThe cold, exact figure of the crip\npled, maimed and disfigured is 1,060,000\n\u2014more than four times the number of\nAmerican doughboys wounded in the\ngreat war.\nWAR ON MONOPOLY\nBY ADMINISTRATION\nSAID INCONSISTENT\nLewis Douglas, Former\nBudget Director, Sees \u2018Bit\nterness\u2019 in Country as\nVery Distressing\nNew York, Dee. 30\u2014(AP) \u2014Lewis W.\nDouglas, former Roosevelt director of\nthe budget, today declared he could\nnot understand why \u201cmonopoly and\nmonopolist practices are bitterly de\nnounced in one field, while the gov\nernment encourages it in others.\"\nIn what he later acknowledged to\nbe an oblique reference to the anti\nmonopoly campaign of Asst Atty-Gen\nRobert H. Jackson, Douglas said the\ngovernment was \"encouraging and\nfostering monopoly in the fields of\nagriculture, money and labor\u201d while\n\u201ca high official\u201d discouraged it in\nindustry.\nAddressing 200 members of the\nAlumni of Columbia University club,\nthe newly-elected principal and vice\nchancellor of McGill university said\nhe was distressed \"at the depth of\nfeeling which prevails throughout the\nUnited States.\u201d\n\"And I am distressed at the bitter\nness with which public officials speak\nabout private industry and the bitter\nness with which private individuals\nspeak of public officials,\u201d he added.\nDouglas, who parted company with\nthe administration in 1934 because his\nbudget policies failed to win the Presi\ndent's approval, said the conservatives\nwere \"not wholly without blame in\nintroducing the collectivist idea in\nthis world.\"\n'The protective tariff is one of the\n1 important causes of the destruction\n!of the gold standard,\u201d he went on.\n\"I think, if you could look back on\nthe industry of the last 30 years,\nthe policy of protection, initiated in\nthe \u20197o's, has had the ultimate end\nof bringing down the gold standard.\n'The protective tariff policy, be\ncause of the destruction of the gold\nstandard, has had a profound influence\non present conditions. I can see no\ndifference in logic or reason in the\ngranting of a protective tariff to\none group and granting other kinds\nof subsidies to other groups.\u201d\nIf the conservatives cherish liberty\nand freedom, he said, they \"must re\nassess some of the views they have\npersistently followed.\u201d\n\u2018HONOR\u2019 CONVICTS\nHEAD FOR PRISONS\n550 Ending Two Weeks'\nVacation\u2014One in Hospital\n\u2014Two Phone They Missed\nBusses\nMontgomery, Ala., Jan. 2\u2014(AP)\nConvicts\u2014a majority of Alabama's 55(1\n\"most worthy\" ones\u2014drifted back ti,\nprisons today to keep a \"Word of\nhonor\" agreement to return from\nChristmas paroles on time.\nToday marked the end of a two\nweek vacation granted the men and\nwomen for good conduct. They were\nbound only by \u201cword of honor, man\nto-man\u201d pacts with Gov Bibb Graves\nand their wardens to come back.\nThey filtered in from all directions,\nbut at least one didn\u2019t make it. His\nmother called from Huntsville to re\nport him in a hospital suffering from\nan appendicitis attack.\nA \"Nogro woman, who cooks for a\nKilby prison official, telephoned from\nBirmingham that she missed a bus\nand couldn't make the reporting dead\nline, hot added: \u201cI'se on my way.\"\nOne man called from Memphis, be\ncause he missed a bus and would be\n\"SO minutes late.\"\nJim Germany, n Negro, who hobbles\non legs off at the knees, got in well\nahead, reporting at 3 this afternoon.\nHe caught a ride from Tuskogee.\nChild Almost Fatally Burned in \u201935\nThrilled to Be Able to Walk Again\nCharleston, W. Va.. .lan. 2 \u2014(AP)\u2014\nFifteen-year-old Betty Jean Boggs\ncelebrated the new year by walking\naround the garage while her fathe.\ngreased the oar, and then went to\nmovie.\nTo Belly, these prosaic deede were\nns thrilling ns anyone could have\nasked\u2014for they meant that after two\nyears and four months of lying fHCe\ndown, she was able to walk normally\nagain.\nEven more exciting was the pros\npect of returning to high school this\nmonth, after an absence of line,\nyears. Because she studied while she\nwas bedfast, she doesn't expert to\nlose more than a year.\nBetty Jean suffered deep burns on\nthe beck from her neck to her heels\nJanuary 4, 1936, when her pajamas\nand bathrobe caught firs from a ga,v\nstove.\nHoliday Weekend Toll\nReaches 217 Lives\n{By the Associated Press, Jan. 3)\nThe btrtlrof the new year meant the\nend of life for more than 217 persona,\nvictims of death by violence in many\nforms, across the nation yesterday.\nMotor traffic fatalities, with driving\nconditions aggravated by snow and ice\nin many places, took the heaviest\nweekend toll with 167 deaths reported\nfrom 38 states.\nSixteen suicides, 14 shootings, six\nfatal burns, four carbon monoxide, two\ndrownings, two heart failures, two\ntrain accidents, and one each In coast\ning, skiing, trolly accident and expos\nure completed the record of tragedy.\nThe death list by states follows:\nAlabama 2, Arkansas 4, California\n11, Colorado 2, Connecticut 3, Florida 4,\nGeorgia 8. Idaho 1, Illinois 29, Indiana\n9, lowa 2, Kansas 3. Kentucky 3, Lou\nisiana 3. Maine 1, Maryland 1, Massa\nchusetts 7, Michigan 6, Minnesota 1,\nMississippi 1, Missouri 9, Montana 1,\nNew Jersey 9, New York 33, North\nCarolina 3. Ohio 15, Oklahoma 3, Penn\nsylvania 14, Rhode Island 1. South\nCarolina 1. Tennessee 4. Texas 13,\nWashington 3, West Virginia 1, Wis\nconsin 7 and Wyoming 1.\nSENATE WILL CALL\nDUPONT AND TAYLOR\nIN PROBING SLUMP\nByrnes Committee to Start\nHearings On Unemploy\nment and Relief, Call Many\nIndustrialists\nWashington, Jan. I\u2014(AP1 \u2014(AP) \u2014A spe\ncial Senate committee investigating\nunemployment and relief plans to hear\ntestimony by du Pont and\nMyron C. Taylor.\nChairman Byrnes (D., S. C.) said to\nday his committee would start hear\nings Tuesday, with federal statistical\nexperts outlining the extent of the\nunemployment problem.\nPresident William Knudsen of Gen\neral Motors, whose company has an\nnounced the layoff of 30,009 men, has\nbeen asked to appear Thursday.\nByrnes saying the committee was\nseeking information on how long the\neconomic downturn might continue,\nsaid du Pont and Taylor would be\nasked to testify some time during the\nweek of the 9th.\nThe South Carolina senator recalled\ndu Pout's recent speech advocating a\nbusiness-government program for re\nviving industry, and said du Pont\n1 might elaborate in testimony before\nthe committee. Taylor, as president of\nthe United States Steel company, is ex\npected to give information on the ex\ntent of unemployment in steel and to\noutline any suggestions he may have\nfor increasing employment.\nOther Witnesses\nOther witnesses to be heard, Byrnes\nsaid, include President J. J. Pelley of\nI the American Association of Railroads;\nC. T. Murchison, representing the tex\ntile industry; Chairman Virgil Jordan\nof the National Industrial Conference\nboard; Louis Kerstein, Boston mer\nchant; R. E. Henry, president of the\nSouthern Cotton Manufacturers\u2019 asso\nciation. and Wilson Compton of the\nNational Lumber Manufacturers\u2019 asso\nciation.\nByrnes said his committee would\nseek to determine the extent and char\nacter of unemployment, would study\npresent government relief methods and\nwould seek to find methods of eliminat\ning unemployment.\nBecause of new problems created by\nthe recession, he said, the committee\nprobably will seek information on its\neffect* and make a tentative report to\nCongress before President Roosevelt\nmakes his relief appropriations recom\nmendation in March.\nEarlier this week. Senator Hatch\n(D\u201e N. M.) suggested that Robert H.\ni Jackson, assistant attorney-general,\nI might be called before the committee\nto elaborate on his recent speeches de\n-1 nouncing \"big business.\"\nj Other committee members said today.\nhowever, that this probably would not\n|be done, because Jaekson's speeches\nj dealt primarily with the question of\nmonopoly rather than unemployment.\nKNUDSEN PUTS OFF\nCOMMITTEE DATE\nG. M. Head Asks Permission\nto Testify January 28 In\nstead of This Week\nOthers to Appear\nDetroit, Dec. 29 \u2014(AP) \u2014William S.\nKnudsen, president of General Motors\nCorp., said today he had asked a\nspecial Senate committee on unem\nployment to postpone his appearance\nlie fore the committee from January\n6 to January 28. He said he was\nentirely willing to testify.\nHe explained that he had planned\nan extensive trip around the coun\ntry. on company business. which\nwould make it inconvenient for him\nto be In Washington untU late In\nthe month. He said he had an en\ngagement in Cincinnati January 6.\nthe day on which he was asked to\ntestify In Washington.\nPhysicians despaired of her life, hut\nmanaged to save her through seven\nblood transfusions.\nAfter a tedious period of recovery.\nMrs N. D. Boggs said, Betty Jeau\n\"even had to learn how to eat sitting\nup all over again, she was so accus\ntomed to eating while lying on her\nstomach.\nShe said her daughter was expected\nto lie \"as good as new\" in time, al\nthough one burn has not yet healed.\nBetty Jean spent the weary months\nin bed knitting, writing and reading\nletters from correspondents in 13\nstates, and a Preabytertan missionary\nin Africa, and rereading a letter from\nPresident Roosevelt\n\"She's trying to make up for lost\ntime now,\" Mrs Boggs said, laughing.\n\"Nobody can leave the house unless\nBetty Jean goes along.\n\"But that's all right with us'\"\nMOBILIZATION PLAN\nWILL BE HEARD AT\nHEARING IN SENATE\n8500 Agencies Represented\nby Group Headed by\nCharles P. Taft\nNew York, Jan. 2\u2014(AP)\u2014The\nburden of caring for the nation's\nunemployed would be shouldered\njointly by the state and federal\ngovernments under a new program\ndrafted by leaders of private phi\nlanthropy for recommendation to\nCongress.\nDescribed as a humane yet eco\nnomical public relief policy for the\nj winter and the next fiscal year, the\nproposal was announced here today\nby the Community Mobilization for\nHuman Needs.\nStates Would Match FJ. S. Fond*\nIt will be outlined to the Senate\ncommittee on unemployment and re\nlief at hearings in Washington, the\n12th. by Chairman Charles P. Taft\nof the organization and associates\nwho spent two mouths framing the\nrecommendations.\nForemost among the recommenda\ntions are provisions for federal ap\npropriations, administered through\nstate and local welfare officials, and\ngranted only on condition that the\nstates put up part of the money and\nmeet certain standards.\nBesides these suggestions for meet\ning immediate needs, Taft and his\ncollaborators, representing more than\n8500 local and national social and\nhealth agencies, will ask for the ap\npointment of a national commission\nto study relief and welfare on a\nlong-term basis.\nRecommendations\nThA welfare workers, invited to Vp\npear before the Senate committee by\nits chairman, Senator James J.\nByrnes (D\u201e S. C.), will ask:\u2014\nThat the federal government appro\npriate to the state money to carry\nout a general relief program, includ\ning work relief. Provision would be\nj made for the care of interstate\ntransients.\nThat federal funds be matched in\nprescribed proportions by the states.\nThat the determination of the\namount and character of work relief\nand of those eligible for relief be pri\nmarily the responsibility of the state\nand local government.\nFederal regulation of standards of\nadministration, and of relief \"within\ngeneral limits\": These standards would\nrequire within each state and city a\nunified, or at least a coordinated ad\nministration. under a merit system of\nappointment, of all public assistance\nand general relief programs to which\nthe government contributes.\n\u201cConfusion in Public Mind\"\n\u2018The human values and the ex\npense involved in relief, security, and\npublic welfare 'programs, and the cur\nrent confusion in the public mind\nabout them,\u201d says the program draft\n\"urgently require a careful and un\nbiased investigation and review by a\nnational commission appointed by the\nPresident and with the approval of\nthe President.\u201d\nAccompanying the announcement of\nthe organization's recommendations\nwas a statement of approval by the\nI national citizens\u2019 committee, which de\ndared the lowering of state and local\nj standards of relief since the federal\n1 government withdrew from responsi\nbility for many of the unemployed\nS has \u201cr esulted In much suffering.\u201d\n\u201cWe face the probability of In\ncreased unemployment this winter and\nI the possibility of a longer recession.\u201d\ni the committee\u2019s statement said. On\nthe other hand, it recognized that the\ni necessity for economy in government\nI expenditures sets a limit to what the\nI government can do.\nPrivate agencies, it explained, even\nlif they were to abandon all other\nservices and devote ail their funds to\nmaterial relief of the unemployed.\nI could muster less than 5 per cent of\nthe amount needed.\nUnemployment Census\nSpurs Demands for Relief\nWashington, Jan. 2\u2014(AP) \u2014The un\nemployment census figures showing\nthat between 7.822,912 and 10,870.000\npersons were unemployed in Novem\nber gave fresh ammunition today to\ncongressional advocates of increased\nrelief and public works expenditures.\nSenator LaFollette (Prog., Wis.)\nsaid tonight in a broadcast address\nthat unemployment was \u201cthe one\nquestion\" which must be answered at\nthe session of Congress beginning to\nmorrow.\n\u201cIt is not economic, it Is not hu\nmane, it is not intelligent to allow\nthis problem to linger unsolved as a\nmenace over the lives of all of us.\u2019\u2019\nhe asserted.\nFrees Big Works Program\nLaFollette advocated a large-scale\nCongress Likely to Be Asked\nFor 10 or IS New Cruisers\nNavy Reported to Have Drawn Such a Supplementary\nProgram\u2014Building Would Be Spread Over Sev\neral Years, With Only Part of Cost Appropriated\nWashington, Dec. 29\u2014(AP) \u2014Naval\nexperts speculated today that Congress\nmight be aakeJ_ to add 10. or IS.\ncruisers to this country's shipbuilding\nprogram as the result of President\nRoosevelt\u2019s \"growing concern\" over re\ncent world events.\nThe federal budget to t\u00bb submitted\nto Congress next week includes re\nquests for funds to start construction\nof two battleships, two light cruisers,\neight destroyers and six submarines.\nMr Roosevelt announced yesterday,\nhowever, that he might send the legis\nlators supplementary estimates tor\ncommencing construction of still more\nships.\nWell informed persons have heard,\nwithout official confirmation, that the\nnavy already has prepared a tentative\nprogram for building 19 to 15 addition\nal cruisers of 10,000 tons each, mount\ning six-inch smns and ousting, at\npresent prices, $20,090,000. or\nmore. each.\nIf such a program is decided upon.\nIt is expected generally that Congress\nwill 1* asked to authorize construc\ntion of the vessels over a period of\nseveral years and to provide actual\nfunds for starting only part of them\nat once.\nCruisers are valuable, officials say.\nto supplement the gun power of bat\ntleships. to scout and screen the move\nments of the slower dreadnnughts, and\nas commerce defenders and raiders.\nBy comparison with the navies of\nGreat Britain and Japan, the United\ni States fleet Is deficient In both heavy\nland light cruisers.\nThe United States now has 1?\n[heavy cruisers and 19 \u201clight\" craft\nof approximately 7900 tons.\nALBUQUERQUE MAYOR\nALLEGED EMBEZZLER\nAlbuquerque, N. M\u201e Dec. 29 \u2014(AP)\u2014 j\nMayor Charles Lembke of Albuquer\nque was charged today with embez- i\nzlement of approximately $12,909 of\ncity funds in a complaint and wa--\nrant issued through the district at\ntorney\u2019s office.\nTen counts were involved, charging\nfraudulent, conversion of city funds to\nMayor Lembke\u2019s own use, from De-\ncember 7, 1334, to June 37, 1935. The\ncomplaint listed Gov Clyde Tingiey.\nformer city commissioner, as one of\n12 witnesses.\nBATTLE PORTENT\nFOR BIG BUSINESS\nSEEN IN ICKES TALK\nSecretary\u2019s Speech Called\nAdded Evidence of Presi\ndent\u2019s Purposes Brake j\nOn Tax Revision Hinted\nWashington, Dec. 30\u2014(AP)\u2014Secre\ntary Ickes\u2019s speech tonight furnished j\nnew signs that President Roosevelt\nis arming for battle, not compromise,\nwith \"big business\u201d at the coming\nsession of Congress. lekes joined\nAsst Atty-Gen Robert H. Jackson in\ntracing the business recession to \u201ca\nsit-down strike\u201d of private capital\ncontroled by \u201cthe 60 families.\u201d and\nserved notice that the administration\nIntended to deal with it \"now.\u201d\nComing on the eve of the session\nand while the President is busy with\npreparation of his message to Con\ngress, the remarks by lekes and Jack\nson are of special significance. Both\nwere the President's guests on his\nFlorida fishing trip during the special\nsession. Both have repeatedly sound\ned discordant notes publicly since\nthen in the harmony of peace-with\nbusiness talk by other administration\nmen.\nMonopoly Issoe Seen Central\nNo hint as to what the President\nwill say in his message next week\nhas leaked from the White House.\nI There is doubt that even lekes and\n1 Jackson yet know his intentions, fa\nmiliar as they may be with his point\nj of view as to underlying causes of\ni the recession. That lekes reflected\nthat point of view when he said to-\nI night that \"the future of America de\n-1 pends upon whether big business can\n\u2014now, within the coming session of\nCongress\u2014be compelled to conform to\nour laws\u201d is generally believed by\nclose observers.\nThe lekes broadcast reenforces ex\npectations that the President, while\npressing anew his drive for othei\nmeasures like wage-hour standards\nlegislation, will concentrate on the\n\"monopoly\u201d issue as the club to force\nthat big business cooperation \"with\nl the rest of us to make democracy\nj work\u201d for which the interior secre\ntary called. Jackson has made that\nI his theme consistently and lekes\ni called attention to the Jackson\ncharges that monopolistic price boost\ning, not new deal tax policies, caused\nj the recession.\nBrake Bn Tax Revision Hinted\nYet the President\u2019s strategy is still\njto be disclosed. His message at the\nbeginning of the special session\nstressed cooperation with business to\nrevive recovery. It contained a flat\ni assertion, however, that \"if private\nenterprise does not respond, govem-\nI ment must take up the stack.\u2019\u2019\nI Whether his forthcoming message\nwill follow the Ickes-Jackson thesis\nthat private enterprise has not re\nsponded and that drastic compulsion\nlis immediately necessary remains to\nbe seen.\nProjecting a congressional study of\n\"monopolistic practices\" in his spe\ncial session message. President Roose\nvelt called only for \"a further search\nfor additional methods to meet this\nthreat to free competitive enterprise.\u201d\nI Neither Jackson nor lekes have sug\nRested ways and means of procedure.\nTo some observers their increasingly\nemphatic challenges to big business\nsignify a deliberate administration\nr campaign to bring about a eongres\nsional investigation rather than im\nmediate legislation.\npublic works program, financed by\nincreased taxation \u201cbased on ability\nto pay.\u201d\nAsserting public works construction\ncost, the federal government only 30\nto 45 cents an hour of employment\nprovided each worker, he added:\n\"Despite this essential economy of\nthe public works and works progress\nprogram business incessantly insisted\nthat the budget he balanced. Time and\nagain it asserted that if the govern\nment would stop spending, private\nbusiness would carry on. The govern\nment made a tragic mistake when it\nyielded to this demand, for it made\nthis new depression inevitable.\"\nOne 10.909-ton and nine light cruis\ners are l.emg built. In addition. Con\ngress already has authorized the con\nstruction of two additional light\ncruisers\u2014the two in the budget for\nthe next fiscal year.\nGieat Britain has 55 cruisers at\nsea. and 21 light cruisers building\nJapan has 32. and at least four build\ning.\nProposals for increased shipbuilding\nappear certain to stir up a bitter\ncontroversy in Congress.\nLarger naval appropriations drew\nstrong support today from Chairman\nPittman <D.. Nev.) of the Senate\nforeign relations committee, but ve\nhement criticism from Senator Wheel\ner (D.. Mont).\nPittman said an Increased appro\npriation would tie \"the cheapest in\nsurance on earth.\"\n\"We can strengthen our navy with\na few hundred mllllous of dollars so\nthat any single nation will be afraid\nto force us into war,\" he added.\nWheeler declared:\n\u201cWhile 1 am for adequate national\ndefense, there is no necessity for\nspending hundreds of millions of dol\nlars for new battleships.\n\"We ought to spend our money for\nIrrigation, reclamation, flood control\nand road building to add to the capi\ntal nssets of the nation.\nBURNED AS MATCHES FLARE\nBrockton, Jan. 2\u2014 iAP>\u2014Mre Alvera\nHoward. 22, today suffered serious\nburns covering three-quarters of her\nbody after a box of matches flared,\nsetting fire to her nightgown, ss she\nwas lighting a clgarek\n7\nNATIONAL NEWS\nTHIRD NEW DEAL\nASSAULT IN WEEK\nSEEN\nIrreconcilable Conflict of\nPlutocracy and Democ\nracy' Proclaimed\nWashington, Dec. 30\u2014(AP)\u2014Sec\nretary lekes, continuing the a<4-n:n-\nistration\u2019s attack upon \u201cbig easi\nness,\" asserted tonight that tb\u00ab\npower of concentrated wealth \u201cmust\nbe compelled to conform to onr\nlaws\u201d at the coming session of Con\ngress.\nAn \"irreconcilable conflict\" be\ntween \u201cthe power of money and the\npower of the democratic instinct*\u2019\nhas reached such an intensity in re\ncent months,\u201d he said, that it it\n\"clear-that it must be fought\nthrough to a finish\u2014until plutoc\nracy. or democracy\u2014until America\u2019s\n60 families, or America\u2019s 120 mil\nj lion people\u2014win\nThird Assault In Week\nHe spoke by radio, over a nation\nwide hookup. His speech was the\nthird assault, upon \"big busineaa\" to\ncome from within the inner admin\nstration circle within a week. AH\nare regarded as a prelude to Presi\ndent Roosevelt\u2019s message to Congress\nand a drive for antimonopoly legisla\ntion.\nlekes accused concentrated economic\npower of going on a strike against\nthe administration, or threatening to\n'do no business, unless governmental\nrestraints upon business are removed.\nHe said:\n\"To the 129 million people of the\nUnited States, they have made the\nthreat that unless they are free t*\nspeculate free of regulations to pro\ntect the people\u2019s money; unless they\nare free to accumulate through legal\nj tricks, by means of corporations,\nwithout paying their share of taxes;\nunless they are free to dominate the\n-est of us without restrictions on their\nfinancial or economic power: unless\ni they are once more free to do all\nthese things, then the United States\nis to have its first general sit-down\nstrike\u2014not of labor\u2014not of the\nAmerican people\u2014but of the 60 farai\nlies and of the capital created by the\nwhole vmerican people, of which the\n80 families have obtained control\nAsserting that the \"69 families*\nbrought on the depression which be\ngan in 1339. he said the people called\nupon the government to intervene\nand the latter was successful tn re\nstoring prosperity.\n\u201cAnd last spring,* he continued,\ni \"government had the business of ths\ncountry turning over so well that it\nthought it could safely heed the pleas\nof private enterprise to governmest\nto abandon the economic initla\nfive.\n\"And what happened?\n\u2022Two things. First, the 60 families\nthat were master-minding private\nenterprise proved to have learned\nnothing nor forgotten nothing since\n1925 about the management of busi\nness under modern conditions. They\nmade the same mistakes they had\nmade before 1929. They ran the stock\nmarket up and helped it get started\ndown. They did little or nothing to\nincrease the purchasing power of\nlabor to make up for the government\nwithdrawals and then ran prices to\nthe sky. so that the consumer refused\nto spend what they graciously let\nhim earn.\n\u201cPower to Wreck Democracy\"\n\"Second, the 60 families, unwilling\nto learn to do business upon the\ndemocratic terms of 1927, began to\nmake demands and threats.\n\u201cTo the 120 million people of the\nCnited States they have made the\nthreat that the professional operator*\nof the Amertcan economic system, and\nthe professional managers of the\ncapital funds of the Cnited States\n(capital to which every American\nman and woman over four genera\ntions has contributed sweat and blood)\n\u2014will refuse to operate that economic\nsystem, will refuse to let that capital\nbe employed\u2014unless they are once\nmore given full power to wreck\nAmerican democracy in their own\nsweet way.\n\u20186O Families' Mentioned\nBy Ickes Are Named\nNew York. Dec. 30\u2014(AP)\u2014The\nRockfellers head Ferdinand Lund\nbergs list of \"America\u2019s 60 families\"\nwhich Secretary of Interior Harold\nL. Ickes referred to in his addrese\ntonight\nTha phrase \"America's 60 famiHea\"\nwas coined by Lundberg. a financial\nwriter, for the title of his book on\nConcentrations of American Capital\npublished last October.\nLundbergs list was based on 1924\nincome tax returns.\nThe families, in the order he listed\nthem, with the primary sources of\ntheir wealth he gave, follow:\nRockefeller (Standard Oil), Morgan\n(banking). Ford (automobiles). Hark\nness tStandard OU), Mellon (alu\nminum). Vanderbilt (New York Cen\ntral railroad), Whitney (Standard\nOil), the \u201cStandard Oil group\" (Arch\nbold. Rogers. Bedford, Cutler, Flagler,\nPratt. Benjamin).\nDu Pont (chemicals!. McCormick\n(farm machinery and Chicago Tri\nbune). Baker (First National bank).\nFisher (General Motors), Guggenheim\n(American Smelting and Refining\ncompany). Field (Marshall Field de\npartment store). Curtis-Bok tmagazine\npublishing). Duke (American Tobacco\ncompany).\nBerwind (coal). Lehman t banking),\nWidener (American Tobacco and util\nities). Reynolds (R. J. Reynolds To\nbacco company). Astor (real estate).\nWinthrop (miscellaneous). Stillman\n(National City bank). Timken (roller\nhearings). Pitcairn (Pittsburg Plate\nGlass company). Warburg (hanking).\nMetcalf (Rhode Island textile mills),\nClark (sewing machines), I\u2019hippe\n(Steel), Kahn thanking). Green (Stocks\nand real estate). Patterson (Chicago\nTribune). Taft (real estate). Deering\n(farm machinery), De Forest (corpo\nration law), Gould (railroads), HU*\n(railroads), Drexel IJ. P. Morgan\ncompany).\nImllildiial* Paying Family Taxes\nIndicates deceased.)\nThomas Fortune Ryan (stock mar\nket) x. H Foster (automobile peris).\nKldridge Johnson (phonographs). Ar\nthur Curtiss James (copper and rail\nroads), C. W. Nash (automobiles),\nMortimer Schiff (banking) x. James\nA Ratten (wheat market) x.\nCharles Hayden (stock market) x.\nOrlando F. Weber (Allied Chemical\nand Dye corporation), George Blu\ntuenthal (baking). Ogden L. Mills\n(mining) x, Michael Frledsam (mer\nchandising) x, Edward B. McLean\n(mining). Eugene Higgins (New York\nreal estate). Alexander 8. Cochran\n(textiles) x, Mrs L. N. Kirkwood.\nHelen Tyson. Aicher Huntington\n(railroads) x. James J. Storrow (brok\nerage) x, Julius Rosenwald (Sear*\nRoebuck) x. Bernard M Baruci,\n(Stock market), 8. 8. Kresg* (depart\nment stores).","height":"25932","width":"19877"}}
